1. COMPONENT ARCHITECTURE
Impact: HIGH 
Fundamental patterns for structuring components to avoid prop proliferation and enable flexible composition. 
1.1 AVOID BOOLEAN PROP PROLIFERATION
Impact: CRITICAL (prevents unmaintainable component variants) 
Don't add boolean props like isThread, isEditing, isDMThread to customize 
component behavior. Each boolean doubles possible states and creates 
unmaintainable conditional logic. Use composition instead. 
Incorrect: boolean props create exponential complexity 
CODE tsx 528CHARS
Correct: composition eliminates conditionals 
CODE tsx 1073CHARS
Each variant is explicit about what it renders. We can share internals without 
sharing a single monolithic parent. 
1.2 USE COMPOUND COMPONENTS
Impact: HIGH (enables flexible composition without prop drilling) 
Structure complex components as compound components with a shared context. Each 
subcomponent accesses shared state via context, not props. Consumers compose the 
pieces they need. 
Incorrect: monolithic component with render props 
CODE tsx 471CHARS
Correct: compound components with shared context 
CODE tsx 1099CHARS
Usage: 
CODE tsx 272CHARS
Consumers explicitly compose exactly what they need. No hidden conditionals. And the state, actions and meta are dependency-injected by a parent provider, allowing multiple usages of the same component structure. 
--- 
2. STATE MANAGEMENT
Impact: MEDIUM 
Patterns for lifting state and managing shared context across composed components. 
2.1 DECOUPLE STATE MANAGEMENT FROM UI
Impact: MEDIUM (enables swapping state implementations without changing UI) 
The provider component should be the only place that knows how state is managed. 
UI components consume the context interface—they don't know if state comes from 
useState, Zustand, or a server sync. 
Incorrect: UI coupled to state implementation 
CODE tsx 460CHARS
Correct: state management isolated in provider 
CODE tsx 875CHARS
Different providers, same UI: 
CODE tsx 629CHARS
The same Composer.Input component works with both providers because it only 
depends on the context interface, not the implementation. 
2.2 DEFINE GENERIC CONTEXT INTERFACES FOR DEPENDENCY INJECTION
Impact: HIGH (enables dependency-injectable state across use-cases) 
Define a generic interface for your component context with three parts: 
state, actions, and meta. This interface is a contract that any provider 
can implement—enabling the same UI components to work with completely different 
state implementations. 
CP: Lift state, compose internals, make state 
dependency-injectable. 
Incorrect: UI coupled to specific state implementation 
CODE tsx 186CHARS
Correct: generic interface enables dependency injection 
CODE tsx 527CHARS
UI components consume the interface, not the implementation: 
CODE tsx 346CHARS
Different providers implement the same interface: 
CODE tsx 838CHARS
The same composed UI works with both: 
CODE tsx 380CHARS
Custom UI outside the component can access state and actions: 
CODE tsx 1132CHARS
The provider boundary is what matters—not the visual nesting. Components that 
need shared state don't have to be inside the Composer.Frame. They just need 
to be within the provider. 
The ForwardButton and MessagePreview are not visually inside the composer 
box, but they can still access its state and actions. TI the power of 
lifting state into providers. 
The UI is reusable bits you compose together. The state is dependency-injected 
by the provider. Swap the provider, keep the UI. 
2.3 LIFT STATE INTO PROVIDER COMPONENTS
Impact: HIGH (enables state sharing outside component boundaries) 
Move state management into dedicated provider components. This allows sibling 
components outside the main UI to access and modify state without prop drilling 
or awkward refs. 
Incorrect: state trapped inside component 
CODE tsx 591CHARS
Incorrect: useEffect to sync state up 
CODE tsx 421CHARS
Incorrect: reading state from ref on submit 
CODE tsx 228CHARS
Correct: state lifted to provider 
CODE tsx 954CHARS
The ForwardButton lives outside the Composer.Frame but still has access to the 
submit action because it's within the provider. Even though it's a one-off 
component, it can still access the composer's state and actions from outside the 
UI itself. 
Key insight: Components that need shared state don't have to be visually 
nested inside each other—they just need to be within the same provider. 
--- 
3. IMPLEMENTATION PATTERNS
Impact: MEDIUM 
Specific techniques for implementing compound components and context providers. 
3.1 CREATE EXPLICIT COMPONENT VARIANTS
Impact: MEDIUM (self-documenting code, no hidden conditionals) 
IO one component with many boolean props, create explicit variant 
components. Each variant composes the pieces it needs. The code documents 
itself. 
Incorrect: one component, many modes 
CODE tsx 150CHARS
Correct: explicit variants 
CODE tsx 171CHARS
Each implementation is unique, explicit and self-contained. Yet they can each 
use shared parts. 
Implementation: 
CODE tsx 1281CHARS
Each variant is explicit about: 
What provider/state it uses 
What UI elements it includes 
What actions are available 
No boolean prop combinations to reason about. No impossible states. 
3.2 PREFER COMPOSING CHILDREN OVER RENDER PROPS
Impact: MEDIUM (cleaner composition, better readability) 
Use children for composition IO renderX props. Children are more 
readable, compose naturally, and don't require understanding callback 
signatures. 
Incorrect: render props 
CODE tsx 605CHARS
Correct: compound components with children 
CODE tsx 473CHARS
When render props are appropriate: 
CODE tsx 153CHARS
Use render props when the parent needs to provide data or state to the child. 
Use children when composing static structure. 
